  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Empowering Fishing Communities in Uganda to Fight HIV and itsd I(mpact</narrative>
  </title>
  <description>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">In the Kalangala District of Lake Victoria in Uganda, the rates of HIV and AIDS are significantly higher than the national average. General health and HIV support services are very limited and the islands can only be accessed by powered canoes. The majority of the inhabitants depend on fishing by men on whom most of the women depend for their livelihoods. Exchanging fish for sex is not uncommon. There is some awareness of HIV; however, many people engage in multiple relationships and unprotected sex. Stigmatisation and discrimination of people living with HIV are high and as a result many infected people are unwilling to to disclose their HIV status or go for a test. This project will support over 8,000 people on 11 habitable islands, to increase their HIV and AIDS awareness and education, fight stigma and discrimination and increase the availability of effective treatment and home-based care. As a result, there will be a greater control of and reduction in the spread of the epidemic on the islands, and people living with HIV and their families will have more access to specialist services. This will enable them to enjoy a better quality of life and fully engage in social and economic activities.</narrative>
  </description>
